---- ALGORITHMS ----

> > C2: Explain how you read and write to the console for the kernel monitor.

> The kernel monitor will reads input one character at a time from the Pintos input layer using `input_getc()`. Each typed character is echoed back to the console with `putchar()`, and the command is terminated when a newline is received. Output is printed using `printf()`. After a full line is read into a small fixed-size buffer, the monitor compares the command string against `whoami` and `exit`. Any other input prints `invalid command`.

> > C3: Any additional enhancement you implement?

> I add a small additional enhancement to support for backspace/delete during command entry. When the monitor detects delete/backspace input, it will removes the most recent character from the command buffer, updates the null terminator, and erases the character from the console display. Also, empty input lines are ignored and we will simply redisplay the prompt.
